# plt.xlim(-0.02,0.05)
# Seb: if I understand right, delta_score = s_{t+k} - s_{t}
# But that would suggest that most of the time the score is *increasing*, so that can't be right.
# Presumably it is delta_score = s_{t} - s_{t+k}

# In our equations s_{t+k} = s_{t} + e
# so -e = delta_score

<AxesSubplot:xlabel='delta_score', ylabel='Density'>
{% endraw %} {% raw %} 
# delta_score = log[s_{t}] - log[s_{t+k}] = -\epsilon
# delta_score = log[s_{t}/s_{t+k}]
log_epsilon_array = np.log(original_scores / updated_scores)
{% endraw %} {% raw %} 
log_epsilon_array.shape

(5, 57912)
{% endraw %} {% raw %} 
log_epsilon_pd = pd.DataFrame(log_epsilon_array.T, columns=[i+1 for i in range(5)])
log_epsilon_pd_melt = pd.melt(log_epsilon_pd, var_name="acquisition_size", value_name="log_epsilon")
sns.kdeplot(data=log_epsilon_pd_melt, x="log_epsilon", hue="acquisition_size")
plt.xlim(-.05, 0.025)

{% endraw %} {% raw %} 
from tqdm import tqdm
from scipy.stats import gumbel_r, gumbel_l
gumbel_r_fits = []
gumbel_l_fits = []
for batch in tqdm(log_epsilon_array):
    gumbel_r_fits.append(gumbel_r.fit(batch))
    gumbel_l_fits.append(gumbel_l.fit(batch))


print(f"gumbel_r_fits={gumbel_r_fits}")
print(f"gumbel_l_fits={gumbel_l_fits}")
